<h3>Presentation 1: Morally excluding (some) animals: The role of human
supremacy beliefs and perceived vegetarianism threat.
</h3>

<h3>
Authors
</h3>
<p>
Ana C Leite, Kristof Dhont, Gordon Hodson, Ariel Cheng, and
Tong Zhou
</p>
<h4>Speaker: Ana C Leite  (Durham University)
</h4>
<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
In this project we were interested in studying the moral exclusion of
different animals and how this may be predicted by ideologically motivated
beliefs. Previous research found that stronger beliefs in human supremacy
over animals, and stronger perceived threat posed by vegetarianism to
traditional practices, are associated with stronger speciesism and more
meat consumption (Dhont &amp; Hodson, 2014). Both variables might also be
implicated in the moral exclusion of animals. We tested this in a 16-month
longitudinal study in the USA (N = 219) and in a cross-sectional study in
China (N = 242). Results found that human supremacy beliefs were
associated with the moral exclusion of all animal categories in both studies.
In Study 1 (but not Study 2) we also found that vegetarianism threat
predicted moral exclusion of food animals (e.g., cows and pigs), and,
unexpectedly, appealing wild animals (e.g., chimps and dolphins). These
findings demonstrate the importance of human supremacy beliefs in
explaining moral exclusion of all animals and highlight that in some cultures
vegetarianism threat may play a role in explaining the moral exclusion of
(some) animals.
</p>

<h3>
Presentation 2: Beauty of the Beast: Beauty as an independent
dimension in the moral standing of animals
</h3>

<h3>
Authors
</h3>
<p>
Christoph Klebl, Yin Luo, Nicholas Poh-Jie Tan, Judah Teo Ping
Ern, and Brock Bastian
</p>

<h4>Speaker: Christoph Klebl (The University of Melbourne)
</h4>
<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
Conservationists have sought to identify avenues through which to gain
public support for efforts to halt the accelerating decline in animal diversity.
Previous research has identified internal qualities of animals that lead
people to view them as deserving of protection for their own sake; that is,
increase their moral standing. In two studies, we found that beauty is an
external aesthetic quality that leads people to attribute moral standing to
animals independently from animals’ mental capacities associated
with patiency or agency, and dispositional harmfulness. In Study 1, we
found that beauty perceptions independently predicted moral standing
across a wide range of animal species from 12 biological categories. In
Study 2 (pre-registered), we found that beauty causally influenced moral
standing attributions to animals independently from animals’ internal
qualities. Our findings provide insight into another factor which contributes
to the perceived moral status of animals, and therefore may help
conservationists to identify the most effective ways to attract funds for
conservation efforts.
</p>
