<h3>
Presentation 3: Sharing reality with animals: Examples and
implications for humans and other animals in agricultural settings
<h3>
Authors
</h3>
<p>
Erin B. Ryan, and Becca Franks
</p>

<h4>
Speaker: Erin B. Ryan (University of British Columbia)
</h4>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
Animal agriculture, a system that employs 1.3 billion people and results in
the slaughter of over one hundred billion animals each year, represents
perhaps the most profound intertwining of human and animal lives on the
planet. And yet, research on the human-animal relationships at the centre
of these systems has focused on only a narrow range of relationship states.
In this talk, we use Shared Reality as a framework to review the
scholarship in favour of expanding that range to include close,
intersubjective relationships. Looking toward traditions that encourage
learning from and taking the perspective of nonhuman animals, we provide
entry points into a discussion of the methods and advocacy that can close
the human-animal relational divide in agriculture. By showing that close
relationships are possible and likely of mutual benefit, this research
highlights an additional and underrecognized harm incurred by the
industrialization of our food systems.
</p>

